Package CombinedCodes

Class Fraction

java.lang.Object
CombinedCodes.Fraction
Direct Known Subclasses:
MixedFraction
public class Fraction extends Object
The Fraction class represents a fraction with numerator and denominator attributes. This class contains constructors, setter and getter methods, and methods to perform basic operations on fractions, such as arithmetic operations and reducing a fraction to its simplest form. This class also includes methods to represent a fraction as a String and as a double.

    • divideBy

      public Fraction divideBy(Fraction fraction2)
      Divides this fraction by the given fraction and returns the quotient as a new Fraction. If either the numerator or denominator of the second fraction is equal to 0, this method returns a new Fraction (1/0) that results in Undefined. This is because when the numerator or denominator of `fraction2` equals 0, then `fraction2` results in either 0 or undefined. Hence, `fraction1` cannot be divided by 0 or undefined, as the result will be undefined indefinitely.

    • reduce

      public Fraction reduce()
      Simplifies the fraction to its simplest form by dividing both the numerator and denominator by their greatest common divisor (GCD), then returns the simplified fraction.

    • toMixedFraction

      public MixedFraction toMixedFraction()
      This method toMixedFraction makes and converts the fraction to mixed fraction if applicable This method is utilized specifically for multiplyBy and divideBy because we need first the improper fraction to execute the operation. The resulting product or quotient will be converted again to mixed fraction, thus the creation of this method.
      Returns:
      new MixedFraction

    • toString

      public String toString()
      Returns a string representation of the fraction as "numerator/denominator". If the denominator is 0, it returns "Undefined". If the denominator is negative, both the numerator and denominator are multiplied by -1 so that a fraction with a negative denominator will not be displayed as "numerator/-denominator," but "-numerator/denominator." For example, if the original fraction is 5/-9, the fraction would be returned as a String as "-5/9".
